## HIGH — Implement Second (Operational Reliability)

### 3. Add OrderGroup for receipt and refund traceability

**Risk: HIGH. A customer who checks out 3 meals generates 3 Order rows tied to 1 Stripe charge. There is currently no single model representing "this payment." Refund handling and receipt emails require reconstructing this from 3-hop joins.**

Add to schema:

```prisma
model OrderGroup {
  id                    String          @id @default(cuid())
  checkoutSessionId     String          @unique
  checkoutSession       CheckoutSession @relation(fields: [checkoutSessionId], references: [id])
  stripePaymentIntentId String?
  totalCharged          Decimal         @db.Decimal(10, 2)
  currency              String          @default("cad")
  orders                Order[]
  receiptSentAt         DateTime?
  createdAt             DateTime        @default(now())
  updatedAt             DateTime        @updatedAt

  @@index([stripePaymentIntentId])
}
```

Add `orderGroupId String?` and the corresponding relation to the `Order` model. Populate `orderGroupId` in the Stripe webhook handler at the same time orders are created.

### 4. Add checkoutSessionId to Order

**Risk: HIGH. No direct FK from Order to CheckoutSession. Admin support queries require 3 joins to answer "what session created this order?"**

Add to `Order` model:

```prisma
checkoutSessionId String?
checkoutSession   CheckoutSession? @relation(fields: [checkoutSessionId], references: [id], onDelete: SetNull)
```

Populate this in the same webhook handler that creates orders. Write a backfill script that traces existing orders via `orderIntentId → CheckoutSessionItem → checkoutSessionId` and populates the new column.

### 5. Add OrderStatusEvent audit log

**Risk: HIGH. When an admin changes fulfillmentStatus (e.g., marks DELIVERED when it wasn't), there is no record of who changed what or when. This is a liability issue with real consumers.**

Add to schema:

```prisma
model OrderStatusEvent {
  id         String            @id @default(cuid())
  orderId    String
  order      Order             @relation(fields: [orderId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)
  fromStatus FulfillmentStatus
  toStatus   FulfillmentStatus
  changedBy  String            // userId of the admin or system
  reason     String?           @db.Text
  createdAt  DateTime          @default(now())

  @@index([orderId])
  @@index([createdAt])
}
```

Update every place in the codebase that writes `fulfillmentStatus` to also insert an `OrderStatusEvent` row in the same transaction. Never update `fulfillmentStatus` outside of a transaction that also creates this event.

### 6. Add adminNotifiedAt to FailedOrder

**Risk: HIGH. A Stripe payment succeeds but order creation fails. The FailedOrder row is created but no human is guaranteed to see it.**

Add to `FailedOrder` model:

```prisma
adminNotifiedAt DateTime? // set when an alert (email/Slack/etc.) is successfully sent
lastRetryAt     DateTime?
nextRetryAt     DateTime?
```

Ensure the webhook handler that writes `FailedOrder` rows also triggers a notification (email or Slack webhook) immediately. Set `adminNotifiedAt` after the notification is confirmed sent.

